#  Bandwidth Measurement Tools
## **95th percentile**

That is how bandwidth is actually measured and purchased from providers such as level3, cogent, etc.

Basically, the top 5% usage of the is not billed.

So, if a client consumes about 5mbps all the time, but let's say he bursts to 100mbps for 5 hours a month. He WOULD NOT pay for that bandwidth. He would pay for his usual 5mbps.

Why? 5% of the month is 36 hours. So any large bandwidth bursts that do not last more than 35 hours in a month, the client doesn't pay for it.

You actually pay LESS on our method than actual consumption. 95th percentile method allows clients the ability to burst without paying for those bursts.

With 95th percentile, we only bill clients for either outgoing or incoming, NOT BOTH. Whichever is highest. So let's say a client has outgoing 5mbps, and incoming 4mbps. He would only pay for 5mbps, not 9mbps.

With 95th percentile, clients actually PAY LESS.

##  MRTG - Multi Router Traffic Grapher 

What is MRTG

MRTG is written in perl and works on Unix/Linux and in Windows. MRTG is free software licensed under the Gnu GPL. MRTG generates HTML pages containing images which provide a visual representation of server traffic.

Wiki: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi_Router_Traffic_Grapher

Also go to http://oss.oetiker.ch/mrtg for all the details about mrtg.

Some MRTG Examples: http://mrtghelp.com/examplemrtg.htm
How  to See Server Bandwidth Usage

Customers can view their server bandwidth usage from the client portal.

    Login to client portal 
    Go to Menu >> Hosted Servers
    Click on the server name >> Then click on the Bandwidth Tab to see the current traffic on that server
